class Solution {
    public String reverseOnlyLetters(String s) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        Stack<Character> letters = new Stack<>();
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isLetter(c)) {
                letters.push(c);
            } else {
                sb.append(c);
            }
        }
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (Character.isLetter(c)) {
                sb.append(letters.pop());
            } else {
                sb.append(c);
            }
        }
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution utilizes a stack to store the English letters encountered in the string. It iterates through the string twice: first to push letters onto the stack and second to pop letters from the stack and append them to the StringBuilder in reversed order. Non-letter characters are appended directly to the StringBuilder.

